1
00:00:02,899 --> 00:00:28,434
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato sambha sambhudassa Namo tassa bhagavato arahato sambha sambhudassa Namo tassa bhagavato arahato sambha sambhudassa

2
00:00:28,533 --> 00:00:33,158
Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble, and fully self-awakened one.

3
00:00:36,883 --> 00:00:45,213
Let me just see if I can...

4
00:00:45,234 --> 00:00:46,575
Okay.

5
00:00:46,594 --> 00:00:46,936
Right.

6
00:00:47,095 --> 00:00:52,902
This evening, I thought we'd tackle this...

7
00:00:55,786 --> 00:01:23,802
advice that the buddha gives us so as you know ananda was the buddha's attendant for the last 20 years of his life he was his cousin and he would listen to all the buddha's talks and he had a contract with the buddha when he took on this work that he would the buddha would always relate to him anything he'd said when he wasn't there and he had this phenomenal audio memory

8
00:01:26,093 --> 00:01:31,706
And he would say things, give his opinion, and the Buddha would gently correct him, you see.

9
00:01:32,387 --> 00:01:37,900
So one was, you know, that he had now really come to understand dependent origination.

10
00:01:38,460 --> 00:01:44,254
And the Buddha said, oh, no, Ananda, dependent origination is deep, profound, etc., etc.

11
00:01:44,469 --> 00:01:48,617
Well, he sort of made the same mistake when it came to the spiritual life.

12
00:01:49,418 --> 00:01:57,152
Ananda said that he thought good friendship, good companionship and good comradeship were half the spiritual life.

13
00:01:57,753 --> 00:02:08,570
And the Buddha said, oh Lord, it is the entire spiritual life, Ananda, that is good friendship, good companionship, good comradeship.

14
00:02:08,921 --> 00:02:21,737
When a person has a good friend, a good companion and a good comrade, it is to be expected that they will develop and cultivate the Noble Eightfold Path.

15
00:02:21,758 --> 00:02:25,782
In other words, your kalyanamita, your spiritual friend.

16
00:02:25,802 --> 00:02:33,512
So if we just look at those three things and just arbitrary definitions of these different words,

17
00:02:33,965 --> 00:02:39,372
If we take good companionship, so a companion is usually somebody who travels with you, you know.

18
00:02:40,133 --> 00:02:49,467
So really, it's those who are closest to you, your spouse, your partner, your very close friend.

19
00:02:50,367 --> 00:02:55,495
And you can understand that, you know, let's take partners, for instance.

20
00:02:55,675 --> 00:03:01,103
If both of them are actually on the same path, I mean, that's a tremendous refuge, isn't it?

21
00:03:01,336 --> 00:03:08,986
Even if one is a Tibetan and the other one is a Theravada, I'm sure they can find some support for each other.

22
00:03:10,848 --> 00:03:14,974
So there's that sort of intimacy, an intimate relationship.

23
00:03:15,275 --> 00:03:22,365
If that intimate relationship and the both people are actually on the same path, that's obviously a great support.

24
00:03:23,897 --> 00:03:31,787
On a wider level, so we talk about good friendship, they're all the ones, they're all the people whom you know, apart from those who are close to you.

25
00:03:32,668 --> 00:03:52,352
And I think some of you will have found, like I did, that as I moved into the Dharma, became more and more involved, I found that I was losing my interest in the theatre, the local semi-professional theatre that we had in Birmingham at the time.

26
00:03:52,602 --> 00:03:54,062
And eventually I stopped going.

27
00:03:54,484 --> 00:03:57,926
I didn't actually say goodbye to anybody.

28
00:03:58,527 --> 00:04:02,491
When I look back, I didn't say goodbye to anybody and tell them what I was doing.

29
00:04:03,112 --> 00:04:05,675
I just faded out, you might say.

30
00:04:06,475 --> 00:04:11,121
And interestingly enough, I can't remember meeting any of them again.

31
00:04:11,181 --> 00:04:17,567
And that's part of that movement towards a spiritual life for me.

32
00:04:18,408 --> 00:04:22,052
And you might have found that also to be true of yourselves.

33
00:04:26,555 --> 00:04:35,336
When it comes to comradeship, so for me, the word comrade, of course, is associated with the Communist Party, you know, Comrade Boris.

34
00:04:36,499 --> 00:04:38,163
I'm not talking about Big Boris, of course.

35
00:04:38,603 --> 00:04:40,007
So he got...

36
00:04:40,088 --> 00:04:48,000
So that gives us a sort of feel that we're in something that is much bigger than just our personal relationships.

37
00:04:48,021 --> 00:04:50,946
And it's something that's very grand.

38
00:04:51,646 --> 00:04:54,011
So Buddhism is, of course, a world religion.

39
00:04:54,552 --> 00:05:02,805
And it's not only got so many million people who are following the Buddhist path, it also has a massive history, two and a half thousand years.

40
00:05:02,785 --> 00:05:07,795
And I think what that does when you reflect on it, it gives you tremendous confidence.

41
00:05:07,836 --> 00:05:22,887
You would have thought by now, after 2,500 years, that people would have sussed out whether the Buddha was telling the truth or not, whether it was just a big telltale.

42
00:05:24,992 --> 00:05:37,021
So when I used to contemplate this about friendship being the entire spiritual life, it never matched up for me.

43
00:05:37,083 --> 00:05:40,149
I couldn't quite work out why it should be the entire life.

44
00:05:40,129 --> 00:05:41,353
spiritual life.

45
00:05:42,136 --> 00:05:44,682
But then of course I came across Ubuntu.

46
00:05:45,023 --> 00:05:49,355
Now some of you will know it as the open source operating system on Linux.

47
00:05:49,776 --> 00:05:51,942
But that's not what I'm actually referring to.

48
00:05:52,002 --> 00:05:55,793
Ubuntu is a South African philosophy

49
00:05:55,773 --> 00:06:06,267
from, say, Zimbabwe downwards, so the Zulus and the Xhosa people, all those people have this philosophy of Ubuntu.

50
00:06:07,189 --> 00:06:12,757
And you can encapsulate it in one small sentence.

51
00:06:13,577 --> 00:06:19,406
I am what I am because of who we all are.

52
00:06:20,887 --> 00:06:25,053
I am what I am because of who we all are.

53
00:06:25,843 --> 00:06:28,187
In other words, I am my relationships.

54
00:06:28,889 --> 00:06:32,495
And I remember, what was his name?

55
00:06:33,196 --> 00:06:35,901
Krishnamurti saying that, actually.

56
00:06:38,425 --> 00:06:50,805
So in the Satipatthana discourse, the Buddha actually, in the four sections, one on the body, one on feeling, one on mental states, and one on the teachings of the Dharma,

57
00:06:52,490 --> 00:06:55,254
There is this recurrent phrase that goes through it.

58
00:06:55,295 --> 00:07:10,144
They meditate observing an aspect of the body or feelings or mental states or teaching of the Dharma internally, externally, both internally and externally.

59
00:07:11,245 --> 00:07:14,952
And it's this last one that I want to sort of center on.

60
00:07:15,845 --> 00:07:25,057
So in other words, the Buddha is asking us to be aware of ourselves, aware of others, but also this interaction that is constantly happening between us.

61
00:07:27,000 --> 00:07:36,752
And if we just take one or two examples, so this body, for instance, I mean, this body that we've got, you know, isn't something we chose.

62
00:07:37,694 --> 00:07:40,096
I definitely would have chose something better, I think.

63
00:07:41,257 --> 00:07:49,293
I just happened to be ended up with this body because of all the genetic history that came before it.

64
00:07:51,458 --> 00:07:54,944
And this body expresses that genetic history.

65
00:07:56,709 --> 00:08:00,516
It's part and parcel of that specific genetic history.

66
00:08:02,351 --> 00:08:21,523
When it comes to the body, you see, the food I eat, not only is it grown by others and sold by others, etc., and often cooked by others for me, the actual recipes that we use are usually made up by other people.

67
00:08:22,064 --> 00:08:27,853
So there's this constant flow of information about what's nice to eat, what makes a good meal.

68
00:08:28,576 --> 00:08:30,858
It's the same with clothes and fashions.

69
00:08:31,821 --> 00:08:32,861
The fashions change.

70
00:08:32,881 --> 00:08:33,984
Who changes them?

71
00:08:34,323 --> 00:08:36,567
Some bright spark has an idea.

72
00:08:36,868 --> 00:08:40,692
And then after that, we're all wearing different clothes.

73
00:08:40,712 --> 00:08:51,347
I mean, in my own life, my pseudo hippie stage went around with flowery pants.

74
00:08:54,111 --> 00:08:56,575
And when we look at our dwellings, these are all

75
00:08:57,989 --> 00:09:01,375
designed by other people, all the furniture we have in it.

76
00:09:02,476 --> 00:09:06,764
And of course, this becomes obvious when you look at different cultures.

77
00:09:06,783 --> 00:09:13,235
And then you see different food, different clothes, different ideas of how houses should look, etc.

78
00:09:16,519 --> 00:09:18,222
And finally, medicines and care.

79
00:09:19,024 --> 00:09:21,168
All these medicines are produced by other people.

80
00:09:21,207 --> 00:09:22,649
They're coming into my body.

81
00:09:23,311 --> 00:09:24,232
They affect me.

82
00:09:25,562 --> 00:09:33,453
So we get this idea that this body isn't static or anything in any way, not physically.

83
00:09:34,575 --> 00:09:38,340
The water that we're drinking, here we've got this chlorine in it.

84
00:09:39,881 --> 00:09:47,351
The air that we're breathing is full of CO2 because of people using fossil fuels and all that.

85
00:09:49,929 --> 00:09:57,581
So you can see that the body itself is in a process of communication with the world around it.

86
00:09:58,802 --> 00:10:04,912
And in terms of other areas, we're actually just expressions of our culture.

87
00:10:08,176 --> 00:10:11,860
The problem is that this sense of self seems so static.

88
00:10:11,922 --> 00:10:12,942
It seems so real.

89
00:10:12,962 --> 00:10:19,211
You don't seem to think you change, except when it's obvious that you change.

90
00:10:20,102 --> 00:10:22,524
You get this sense of substantiality, you know.

91
00:10:22,544 --> 00:10:26,129
But then when you contemplate it, you realize it's just a concept.

92
00:10:26,208 --> 00:10:38,539
And the concept holds us in present time, as it were, but unfortunately creates a wrong relationship.

93
00:10:38,559 --> 00:10:41,022
We've got this word proprioception.

94
00:10:41,142 --> 00:10:44,504
Proprio means self, perception of self, perception of the body.

95
00:10:44,966 --> 00:10:49,570
So you've only got to watch how your body changes, for instance, with whatever you're sitting on.

96
00:10:49,988 --> 00:10:58,118
a chair, a metal bench, an armchair, lying on the bed, doing yoga on the floor.

97
00:10:58,158 --> 00:11:02,623
We're constantly having to negotiate with the environment around us.

98
00:11:02,643 --> 00:11:06,488
And when you're walking with somebody, you have to be in step.

99
00:11:06,727 --> 00:11:09,731
If they're walking too fast, you tell them to slow down.

100
00:11:11,374 --> 00:11:13,897
If you're walking too slow, you tell them to hurry up.

101
00:11:14,256 --> 00:11:16,620
So there's this constant negotiation going on.

102
00:11:21,982 --> 00:11:28,373
If you catch yourself, for instance, with somebody who has authority over you, right?

103
00:11:29,615 --> 00:11:30,836
It could be a policeman, right?

104
00:11:31,618 --> 00:11:34,522
Suddenly you feel guilty anyway, even if you've not done anything wrong, you know?

105
00:11:35,604 --> 00:11:46,100
But you'll notice that when you're with somebody who has authority over you or whom you respect, who is an authority, whether you like it or not, you'll shrink your body, right?

106
00:11:46,120 --> 00:11:50,285
That's how we express that sort of respect or deference.

107
00:11:50,467 --> 00:12:02,879
And in the same way us, you see, when we feel ourselves to be in authority or in authority over, you'll lift the body up, you'll pull your shoulders back.

108
00:12:02,899 --> 00:12:07,163
And all that's to do with communication.

109
00:12:07,624 --> 00:12:18,855
I don't want to spend too much time on this because there was a video I came across about this poor young kid

110
00:12:19,527 --> 00:12:22,672
whose parents thought had an evil spirit.

111
00:12:22,692 --> 00:12:30,163
So as a toddler, they put him in with the chickens and basically he became a chicken.

112
00:12:30,182 --> 00:12:35,652
And when he got too big for the chicken coop, they put him in an old people's home and tied him to a bed.

113
00:12:37,053 --> 00:12:37,975
And this...

114
00:12:38,966 --> 00:12:41,529
A woman called, where is it now?

115
00:12:42,311 --> 00:12:43,331
Elizabeth Clayton.

116
00:12:43,491 --> 00:12:44,013
You can see it.

117
00:12:44,052 --> 00:12:44,753
It's on YouTube.

118
00:12:44,773 --> 00:12:45,653
There are two videos.

119
00:12:45,794 --> 00:12:51,921
One, you see him as a young man and later on as much more socially interactive.

120
00:12:52,442 --> 00:12:54,403
But he's actually standing there like a bird.

121
00:12:54,784 --> 00:12:57,807
He's got his shoulders like this as though they're flopping wings.

122
00:12:58,328 --> 00:12:58,869
It's awful.

123
00:12:59,629 --> 00:13:02,493
And he will never be able to speak, never be able to communicate.

124
00:13:03,474 --> 00:13:06,898
And what that does for me is it puts in sharp relief

125
00:13:07,097 --> 00:13:10,105
how much we owe to our relationships.

126
00:13:15,216 --> 00:13:22,152
Mental states, our mental states are constantly in... Oops, I've lost my page.

127
00:13:22,211 --> 00:13:22,673
What have I done?

128
00:13:25,919 --> 00:13:26,861
Heartbeat is burning.

129
00:13:27,061 --> 00:13:28,461
Yeah.

130
00:13:29,163 --> 00:13:35,149
We'll notice that our mental states are often affected by the people we're with.

131
00:13:35,610 --> 00:13:41,154
So if you're with people who are depressed, who feel down, it pulls you down.

132
00:13:41,215 --> 00:13:45,299
I mean, you might try to lift yourself up, but in the end, you might give in.

133
00:13:45,820 --> 00:13:50,705
Whereas with your people who are in a happy state, who are bubbly, it just lifts you up.

134
00:13:51,245 --> 00:13:55,649
So there's this constant sort of communication at the heart level.

135
00:13:56,609 --> 00:14:03,609
And there's also a communication at perceptual level, at a conceptual level.

136
00:14:04,270 --> 00:14:10,769
Take something like, you know, big concepts like free speech or democracy or something like that.

137
00:14:11,576 --> 00:14:26,625
You can see that what we read in the newspapers, what we hear people say on the television and things like that, what we discuss amongst ourselves, constantly our concepts are beginning to change.

138
00:14:26,745 --> 00:14:27,306
They move.

139
00:14:28,047 --> 00:14:30,751
And what's understood there, there's an actual word for it.

140
00:14:30,871 --> 00:14:32,115
It's called a perception.

141
00:14:33,177 --> 00:14:35,019
So, for instance, we all have.

142
00:14:35,539 --> 00:14:37,062
a concept of an apple.

143
00:14:38,044 --> 00:14:41,831
But every time you see an apple, that concept is slightly changed.

144
00:14:42,793 --> 00:14:46,259
And so it is with these rather more abstract concepts that we have.

145
00:14:47,061 --> 00:14:48,423
And you can see it changes.

146
00:14:48,543 --> 00:14:49,947
These change over time.

147
00:14:50,668 --> 00:14:52,772
I was just thinking about

148
00:14:53,443 --> 00:14:59,770
you know, kings and queens since we have one here and other countries too.

149
00:15:00,511 --> 00:15:04,755
But there was a time when you could insult a king or somebody like that.

150
00:15:04,996 --> 00:15:12,264
It was lèse-majesté and you'd find yourself, you know, being whipped or chucked in a jail or worse.

151
00:15:12,985 --> 00:15:17,190
And if you think about Putin and Xiaoping and Kim Jong-un,

152
00:15:19,481 --> 00:15:28,572
You can see that, you know, depending on the country you're in or where you're at, your concept of how a country ought to be ruled changes.

153
00:15:29,332 --> 00:15:36,039
There are people who will support Putin and Xi Jinping and all that.

154
00:15:36,059 --> 00:15:45,471
And all these concepts we are absorbing and we are doing our own little interpretation of them, but we're in constant communication.

155
00:15:45,490 --> 00:15:45,591
Yeah.

156
00:15:53,215 --> 00:15:59,927
So I think that sort of sums up this statement by the Buddha.

157
00:16:01,350 --> 00:16:02,933
And I just want to return to it.

158
00:16:05,298 --> 00:16:06,922
So this is what the Buddha says, you see.

159
00:16:06,942 --> 00:16:09,586
He says the entire spiritual life

160
00:16:11,136 --> 00:16:15,166
is good friendship, good companionship, and good comradeship.

161
00:16:15,486 --> 00:16:25,610
And when a person has a good friend, a good companion, a good comrade, it is to be expected they will develop and cultivate the Noble Eightfold Path.

162
00:16:25,630 --> 00:16:29,500
And in his life, you remember, he had these six companions.

163
00:16:29,615 --> 00:16:44,187
who probably followed him from those times when he was practicing those absorption states to when he was practicing the ascetic practices of almost starvation, really.

164
00:16:44,769 --> 00:16:49,072
And remember, when he left them, they didn't want to know him.

165
00:16:49,133 --> 00:16:52,216
As far as they were concerned, he'd gone soft.

166
00:16:52,235 --> 00:16:59,081
And when he came back, it took them a while to realize that maybe he'd changed.

167
00:16:59,450 --> 00:17:04,218
There was a conversation there which comes out when he talks about his new understanding.

168
00:17:04,637 --> 00:17:09,065
And he asks them, have you ever heard me speak like this before?

169
00:17:10,406 --> 00:17:15,355
So right there within the Buddha's life, he had these six companions, you know.

170
00:17:17,198 --> 00:17:26,772
And if we then understand that within the concept of Ubuntu, I am what I am because of who we all are, right?

171
00:17:27,731 --> 00:17:29,273
I am my relationships.

172
00:17:32,438 --> 00:17:41,327
So the Buddha is trying to urge us, or at least trying to make us understand that the people surround us are our inspiration, they're our support.

173
00:17:42,388 --> 00:17:44,531
But they're also supposed to be checks, you know.

174
00:17:44,872 --> 00:17:49,317
A good friend tells you when you're not doing things as you ought to be doing them.

175
00:17:51,140 --> 00:17:54,903
So that's what I was centering on.

176
00:17:55,221 --> 00:18:05,333
And I just felt that I had a better concept of what the Buddha was talking about when I came across this teaching or this philosophy of Ubuntu.

177
00:18:07,055 --> 00:18:24,974
So I can only hope my words have been of some assistance, that they have not caused confusion, and that by your development of good friendship, you will complete the Noble Apo path and be fully liberated sooner rather than later.

